      "writtenOn": "2019-09-23T15:04:43Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m not sure I understand the question.  This is the scenario we\u0027re concerned about:\nt0: snapshot A received from iter.Next(), it\u0027s passed through the channel, and the receiver is ready so it doesn\u0027t block, and we\u0027re back to iter.Next().\nt1: snapshot B received from iter.Next() but the receiver is not ready, so we block.\nt2: other changes occur in the DB, they\u0027ll appear in snapshot C\nt3: receiver finishes processing and grabs snapshot B from the channel. Iterator receives snapshot C and blocks while passing it on the channel.\n\nRepeat t2 and t3 indefinitely. The receiver is always one snapshot behind, because the iterator is having to wait on the receiver. This isn\u0027t necessarily a problem, but it breaks the assumption that the receiver is always grabbing an up-to-date snapshot from the channel.",
